entry.title: Flood Watch issued February 7 at 11:17AM AST until February 8 at 6:00AM AST by NWS San Juan PR
entry.summary:
Most of Puerto Rico generally received between 1 and 2 inches of rain, with the highest amounts between 2 and 4 inches or locally higher across portions of the eastern third and northwest Puerto Rico since the event began yesterday. The U.S. Virgin Islands received between 1 and 2 inches of rain with amounts up to 4 inches across St Croix. Therefore, most soils are saturated today, and river levels are running above normal.
Combining the deep-level trough and above-normal moisture will most likely result in 1-3" additional inches for southern/eastern PR and USVI, with the most reasonable worst-case scenario of 2-4" of rain over these sections. All these factors, the weather pattern, and yesterday's rain accumulation, will maintain a high potential for flash flooding and mudslides today. We may also observe strong thunderstorms, gusty winds, and frequent lightning with the strongest activity.
* WHAT...Flash flooding caused by excessive rainfall continues to be possible.
* WHERE...For all of Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands.
* WHEN...Through early Thursday morning.
* IMPACTS...Excessive runoff may result in flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, and other low-lying and flood-prone locations. Creeks and streams may rise out of their banks. Flooding may occur in poor drainage and urban areas. Storm drains and ditches may become clogged with debris.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS... - Widespread showers and thunderstorms will affect the islands today. Deep tropical moisture and southerly steering winds will bring periods of moderate to locally heavy rains, mainly across the U.S. Virgin Islands, and over portions of eastern, southern and western Puerto Rico. Rainfall accumulations should range between 1 to 3 inches. Any additional rainfall today over saturated soils will cause flooding and mudslides in areas of steep terrain. - http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood
